04443nam a22006255i 9780292769731DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211984txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927697317 a10.7560/7703002doi  a(DE-B1597)588821  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aJK2374.T4bB37 1984 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a324.2764/022191 aBarnes, Donna A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFarmers in Rebellion :bThe Rise and Fall of the Southern Farmers Alliance and People's Party in Texas /cDonna A. Barnes. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1984  a1 online resource (238 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- t1 . Introduction -- t2. Sociological Perspectives on Protest Movement Emergence and Development -- t3. A Critique of Structural Strain Theories of Protest Movement Formation -- t4. The Elaboration and Refinement of the Mobilization Perspective on Protest Movements -- t5. The Rise and Development of the Texas Farmers Alliance, 1877-1886 -- t6. Creative Escalation, 1887-1891 -- t7. The Politicization of the Alliance -- t8. The People's Party: An Alliance Protest Strategy, 1892-1894 -- t9. The Betrayal of Alliance Principles -- t10. The Demise of the People's Party -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe years after the Civil War brought struggle to the Southern farmer as the economic mainstay of the South—cotton—steadily dropped in price. Prompted by hard times, farmers in Lampasas County, Texas, gathered in 1877 to discuss what could be done. From these modest origins emerged the National Farmers Alliance and Industrial Union, later known as the Southern Farmers Alliance, a powerful protest movement that played an important role in the formation in 1892 of a new political force, the People's party. In the "solid South," particularly in Texas, large numbers of voters abandoned the Democratic party for the new party. Yet despite this support, the decline of the People's party after 1894 was swift. Farmers in Rebellion recounts the compelling story of these two crucial and closely related movements. Donna A. Barnes examines their developmental histories, asking such important questions as: Under what conditions do protest movements remain weak? Under what conditions do they prosper, amassing large numbers of supporters? And under what conditions do successful protest movements lose their momentum and die? The author explores these complex questions with deft use of archival data that allows her to reflect on the adequacy of the past sociological answers to these questions. Farmers in Rebellion is a book rich in detail and scope in its look at a critical juncture in the growth of national populist movements. Of interest to sociologists, historians, and political scientists, it stands as an important contribution to our understanding of a pivotal time in Texas, and national, history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aPopulismzTexasxHistoryy19th century. 0aPopulism--Texas--History--19th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/77030040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292769731423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292769731/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK